{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477787"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14716"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14716"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.81,0.04,0.07,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58146"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7409"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43605"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3360"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44993"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58146"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of fever, abdominal pain, and dark urine. He has also experienced nausea, vomiting, and poor appetite. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He lives with his family in temporary accommodation with shared bathroom facilities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. He has scleral icterus and a tender, enlarged liver extending 3 cm below the costal margin. There is no splenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 3.2 mg/dL (0.3-1.2)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlanine aminotransferase 850 U/L (10-40)\u003Cbr /\u003EAspartate aminotransferase 780 U/L (10-40)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 380 U/L (100-400)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlbumin 38 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wilson disease","Hepatitis A","Hepatitis C","Hepatitis B","Epstein-Barr virus infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic picture of acute viral hepatitis, with the clinical and epidemiological features most consistent with Hepatitis A virus (HAV) infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E is particularly common in children, especially in settings with poor sanitation. The presentation with fever, abdominal pain, jaundice, and markedly elevated transaminases is typical. The social circumstances (shared bathroom facilities) increase the risk of faecal-oral transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B\u003C/strong\u003E infection in children typically occurs through vertical transmission from mother to child during birth. The acute presentation would be unusual in a six-year-old without risk factors, and the presence of fever would be less common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis C\u003C/strong\u003E rarely presents with acute symptoms, particularly in children. It typically causes a chronic infection that may be asymptomatic for many years before being detected incidentally or through screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E infection can cause hepatitis, but would typically be accompanied by lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly, and atypical lymphocytosis. The degree of transaminitis would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilson disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder of copper metabolism that typically presents in older children or young adults. While it can cause hepatitis, the acute presentation with fever would be unusual, and other features such as Kayser-Fleischer rings would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of Hepatitis A can be confirmed by detecting IgM antibodies in serum. Management is supportive, and most children make a complete recovery without complications. Prevention through improved sanitation and vaccination is key in high-risk populations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatitis A typically presents in children with fever, abdominal pain, and jaundice.","Peak incidence occurs in children under 10 years of age, particularly in areas with poor sanitation.","Diagnosis is confirmed by detecting Hepatitis A IgM antibodies in serum."],"references":["Murlidharan S, Sangle AL, Engade M, Kale AB. The Clinical Profile of Children With Hepatitis A Infection: An Observational Hospital-Based Study. Cureus. 2022 Aug 23;14(8):e28290. doi: 10.7759/cureus.28290. PMID: 36168369; PMCID: PMC9506446."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43605"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14716"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43605","links":{"self":"https://a